The successful conjugation of complex 1 to GQDs@GSH to give 1@GQDs as well as the subsequent self-assembly of AuNPs unto the 1@GQDs nanostructure (Scheme 2), were confirmed using FTIR (Fig. 1
                        ). Due to the presence of π bonds in both GQDs and complex 1, ππ interaction is also possible between the two depending on orientation. Primary amine and amides (such as those present in GQDs@GSH are known to have two “fangs”, while secondary amines and amides have a single peak. For GQDs@GSH, these two peaks occur at 3338 and 3237 cm−1, Fig. 1b, The FTIR spectrum of the 1@GQDs (Fig. 1(c)) on the other hand, shows the presence of a single amide peak around 3321 cm−1. The disappearance of the two peaks (NH) is a result of chemical bonding to carboxyl group of complex 1 to the amino group of the GQDs@GSH. The emergence of a new single peak at 3321 cm−1 confirms the successful conjugation and hence formation of the resultant 1@GQDs. Moreover, shifts in the CO peak positions from 1722 cm−1 in complex 1 (Fig. 1(b)) to 1618 cm−1 in the conjugate (1@GQDs) (Fig. 1
                        (c)) also confirms the formation of an amide bond between the GQDs@GSH and complex 1.

Raman spectroscopy was employed to ascertain the quality of the GQDs@GSH, both alone and when conjugated. The selection of laser excitation wavelength has a significant impact on experimental capabilities, and whilst typically visible excitation is usually used (488, 514.5, 532 and 633 nm) [55,56], the even longer wavelength of 1064 nm laser was employed in this work. This wavelength was chosen since it allows for minimal sample fluorescence and maximising scattering efficiencies. In addition to this, most biological samples are fluorescent at high frequency; therefore, low frequency lasers (longer wavelength) are better suited for biological work. In GQDs, the in-plane vibrations of sp2 bonded carbon atoms result in the G band whereas the D band is the result of out of plane vibrations attributed to the presence of structural defects (sp3 carbons). Fig. 9
                         shows the Raman spectra obtained for GQDs@GSH, 1@GQDs and 1@GQDs-AuNPs. It can be seen (Fig. 9(ii)), that conjugation of the GQDs@GSH to complex 1, resulted in significant shift in the frequency of the D-band from 1287 cm−1 in the GQDs@GSH alone (Fig. 9(i)) to 1420 cm−1 for 1@GQDs (Fig. 9(ii)). The G-band on the other hand, did not show a marked difference between GQDs@GSH alone and 1@GQDs. Similar D and G band positions were observed for 1@GQDs and 1@GQDs-AuNPs (Fig. 9(iii)). Shifts in the Raman frequencies are often indicative of strong π-electron interactions in hybrid materials [57]. This confirms the ππ interaction of GQDs with complex 1 in addition to covalent bonding. The Raman spectra of the GQDs@GSH alone (Fig. 10
                        ) shows the peaks associated with primary amides (-NH2 stretches) found at 3371 and 3251 cm−1 [58]. The disappearance of the NH2 bands in the conjugate further serves as proof of successful conjugation of complex 1 to GQDs@GSH. It also shows the presence of a peak at 2552 cm−1 attributable to the S-H bond stretch [59] which disappears following the assembly of AuNPs (Fig. 10). There is an appearance on a new peak at 306 cm−1 attributable to the SAu bond [59–61], confirming the successful assembly of AuNPs on the Pcs/GQDs@GSH platform.
